class=3D\"sub-menu\">=0A\t<li id=3D\"menu-item-154\" class=3D\"menu-item m=\r\nenu-item-type-post_type menu-item-object-page menu-item-154\"><a href=3D\"htt=\r\np://informfitness.com/informfitness/contact-us/\">Contact us</a></li>=0A\t<li=\r\n id=3D\"menu-item-157\" class=3D\"menu-item menu-item-type-post_type menu-item=\r\n-object-page menu-item-157\"><a href=3D\"http://informfitness.com/informfitne=\r\nss/schedule/\">Schedule</a></li>=0A</ul>=0A</li>=0A</ul>            </naviga=\r\ntion>            =0D=0A    \t</header>        <!-- end of Header -->=0D=0A  =\r\n      =0D=0A=0D=0A        <!-- end of slideshow -->=0D=0A        =0D=0A    =\r\n    <span class=3D\"clear\">&nbsp;</span>=0D=0A        <section id=3D\"maincon=\r\ntents\">=0D=0A        =0D=0A            <section id=3D\"contents\" class=3D\"gr=\r\nid_8\" style=3D\"padding-top:20px;\">=0D=0A            \t<div id=3D\"page\">=0D=\r\n=0A        \t\t                    <div id=3D\"breadcrumbs\">=0D=0A            =\r\n            <!-- Breadcrumb NavXT 4.1.0 -->=0A<span id=3D\"bstart\" style=3D\"=\r\ncolor:#666666;font-weight:bold;\">You are here:</span> <a style=3D\"color:#66=\r\n6666;\" title=3D\"Go to Home.\" href=3D\"http://informfitness.com\">Home</a> &gt=\r\n; <a style=3D\"color:#666666;\" title=3D\"Go to Resources.\" href=3D\"http://inf=\r\normfitness.com/resources/\">Resources</a> &gt; Nutritional Guide            =\r\n        </div>                \t=0D=0A                \t<h2>Nutritional Guide=\r\n </h2>=0D=0A                    <h2>1.=C2=A0What are fats, proteins, and ca=\r\nrbohydrates?</h2>=0A<p>Fats, proteins, and carbohydrates are the three basi=\r\nc building blocks of nutrition. These nutrients supply calories to the body=\r\n, which the body then uses as fuel.</p>=0A<h3>Fats</h3>=0A<p>Despite powerf=\r\nul stigma, fat is NOT the enemy and should not be so demonized by our socie=\r\nty. Contrary to politically correct nutritional advice, fat is in fact vita=\r\nl to our health and its consumption plays a crucial role in any wholesome d=\r\niet. Without the consumption of good fats, both saturated and unsaturated, =\r\nwe=E2=80=99d be in big trouble. The last thing you should do is adhere to a=\r\n fat-free diet!</p>=0A<p>The word &#8216;fat=E2=80=99 is a colloquial term,=\r\n informally meant to identify a collection of fatty acids=E2=80=94molecular=\r\n compounds made up of hydrogen, oxygen, and carbon. The body cannot produce=\r\n the essential fatty acids (omega-3 and omega-6) by itself, yet they are ne=\r\ncessary for brain development, insulate the organs, provide a concentrated =\r\nsource of energy, protect the liver, enhance the immune system, etc., and, =\r\nfor the vainer among us, help keep the hair, nails and skin beautiful. &#82=\r\n16;Fats=E2=80=99 also satiate hunger, act as carriers for important fat-sol=\r\nuble vitamins A, D, E and K, and aid in mineral absorption.</p>=0A<p>Howeve=\r\nr, of paramount importance is our choice of fats (and oils), and from which=\r\n sources, we choose to consume. Fat from whole, natural food sources should=\r\n not be feared. Traditional animal fats, those found in beef from grass-fed=\r\n cows, their dairy products (including cheese, cream and high-quality, orga=\r\nnic butter), and eggs from pasture-fed chickens are all &#8216;good fats.=\r\n=E2=80=99 Cold-pressed oils from certain vegetable sources, such as olives,=\r\n flax seeds and coconuts, and nuts are also wholesome, nutritious, and esse=\r\nntial fats.</p>=0A<p>&#8216;Hydrogenated=E2=80=99 fats or trans-fats are th=\r\ne REAL enemy! Found in all processed foods, &#8216;bad fats=E2=80=99=E2=80=\r\n=94 those highly refined, heat damaged, and/or man-made=E2=80=94should be f=\r\neared and avoided like the plague. Not only do these bad fats block essenti=\r\nal fatty acids, but are associated with a host of chronic illnesses and dis=\r\neases.</p>=0A<h3>Protein</h3>=0A<p>Protein is vital to our health and prote=\r\nins are found in every part of our bodies=E2=80=94organs, nerves, muscles, =\r\nand again, four hair, nails, and skin. Proteins are critical for cellular g=\r\nrowth, hormone formation, and organ function.</p>=0A<p>While proteins can b=\r\ne comprised by any combination of up to 20 amino acids, 9 of those amino ac=\r\nids are considered &#8216;essential=E2=80=99, again meaning that the body c=\r\nannot manufacture them and they therefor must come from our diet.</p>=0A<p>=\r\nComplete proteins come from animal sources, such as meat, fish, eggs, and c=\r\nheese, and contain all twenty amino acids, including the nine essential ami=\r\nno acids. Meanwhile, incomplete proteins from vegetable sources, such as le=\r\ngumes, lack one or more of the essential amino acids. However, incomplete p=\r\nroteins, such as pulses, can be combined with other incomplete proteins, su=\r\nch as grains, to offer the same nutrients as their more complete counterpar=\r\nts. One perfect example is the classic staple combination of rice and beans=\r\n=E2=80=94two incomplete proteins that when eaten together provide all 9 ess=\r\nential amino acids.</p>=0A<h3>Carbohydrates</h3>=0A<p>Carbohydrates, or &#8=\r\n216;carbs,=E2=80=99 as they are often called, also play an important role i=\r\nn our diets. Carbs provide quick fuel for our bodies that can be digested m=\r\nore quickly than proteins or fats, and break down into glucose (blood sugar=\r\n) when ingested. But the carb story is not quite that straightforward.</p>=\r\n=0A<p>Carbohydrates are classified into two main groups: &#8216;simple=E2=\r\n=80=99 carbohydrates and &#8216;complex=E2=80=99 carbohydrates.</p>=0A<p>Si=\r\nmple carbohydrates are, essentially, sugars. Fruit, some vegetables, milk a=\r\nnd milk products all contain natural sugar, while the sugars found in candy=\r\n, soda, alcohol, white bread, and white sugar are consider to be refined. F=\r\nruit, vegetable and milk product sugars are counteracted, however, by the c=\r\nritical nutrients, vitamins, and proteins these natural sugar sources conta=\r\nin. Meanwhile, refined sugars prove to be the real health-robbers.</p>=0A<p=\r\n>Complex carbohydrates are higher in fiber and take longer to break down in=\r\nto glucose. Complex carbs can be found in legumes, starchy vegetables, and =\r\nwhole grain products, such as brown rice and whole wheat bread. Fruit, vege=\r\ntables (especially members of the cruciferous family, like kale, broccoli a=\r\nnd cauliflower), and beans are especially rich in dietary fiber.</p>=0A<p>F=\r\nor years, traditional nutritionists have recommended that carbohydrates com=\r\nprise a whopping 45% of your daily caloric intake. In recent years, however=\r\n, scientists and nutritionists alike have begun to agree that the most whol=\r\nesome and nutritious diets contain nowhere near that percentage.</p>=0A<p>&=\r\nnbsp;</p>=0A<h2>2. What is glycogen?</h2>=0A<p>Glycogen is glucose (blood s=\r\nugar) stored in the muscles and liver and acts as a reservoir of energy for=\r\n the body. The great majority of a person=E2=80=99s glycogen is located in =\r\nthe muscles (specifically our fast-twitch muscles), ready to provide instan=\r\nt fuel in emergency situations (running away from a bear, chasing down the =\r\nlocal bus, or fighting over the last flat screen TV at a Black Friday Blowo=\r\nut Sale).</p>=0A<p>Just as driving without a spare tire in the trunk of you=\r\nr car is never a good idea, your body knows that operating with depleted gl=\r\nycogen levels compromises the body=E2=80=99s ready energy resources to figh=\r\nt for survival when in dire straits. Thus, when the body=E2=80=99s glycogen=\r\n levels are depleted through the <em>Power of 10</em> high-intensity exerci=\r\nse, the body gets nervous and, in reaction, works frantically to replace th=\r\ne muscles=E2=80=99 lost glycogen=E2=80=94or top off the air pressure in tha=\r\nt spare tire, so to speak.</p>=0A<p>However, when your diet is not laden wi=\r\nth refined carbohydrates and sugar, owing to smart food choices, your gluco=\r\nse will be low and the body will resort to burning fat in order to produce =\r\nthe needed energy. Similarly, when refined carbohydrates and sugars are pro=\r\nminent in your diet (and, as a result, you have high blood sugar) your body=\r\n will use that readily available sugar for fuel, leaving those unwanted fat=\r\n stores intact.</p>=0A<p>&nbsp;</p>=0A<h2>3. What=E2=80=99s the best diet t=\r\no follow in concert with <em>Power of 10</em>?</h2>=0A<p>Tragically, we liv=\r\ne in a world where you can go a week without seeing a real vegetable. &#821=\r\n6;Food=E2=80=99 comes in cardboard boxes, airtight canisters, and plastic b=\r\nags. One can of soup contains more ingredients than words in a Dickens nove=\r\nl and chickens are bred to have so much breast meat they topple over whenev=\r\ner they try to walk. If you cannot pronounce the ingredients in your foods,=\r\n or they promise a shelf-life longer than the life of an average house pet,=\r\n don=E2=80=99t eat them. These traits are not signs of healthy diet choices=\r\n and have to change. Fortunately, some (and now you) are now moving toward =\r\na more sane approach to food and nutrition.</p>=0A<p>Put simply, the best d=\r\niet is one based around real, whole foods. Eating whole foods and controlli=\r\nng your blood sugar are the keys to losing fat, gaining strength, and livin=\r\ng a healthy life. So make the extra trip to the farmers market, visit a but=\r\ncher that only sells free-range chicken and grass-fed beef, and grow spinac=\r\nh and strawberries in your backyard. Your body will thank you.</p>=0A<p>&nb=\r\nsp;</p>=0A<h3>Good Foods</h3>=0A<p>The following is a list of real, whole f=\r\noods you should be building your new healthy diet around. Whenever possible=\r\n, do strive to purchase from organic sources.</p>=0A<p>Proteins (both lean =\r\nand with healthy fat): meat and eggs from free-roaming chickens, turkeys, a=\r\nnd game, grass-fed beef (and associated dairy products), lamb, pork, veal, =\r\nfish and shellfish.</p>=0A<p>Vegetables (the more colorful, the better): Ar=\r\ntichokes, broccoli, cabbage, cauliflower, celery, cilantro, eggplant, garli=\r\nc, ginger, green beans, kale, leafy salad greens, mushrooms, okra, onions, =\r\nparsley, peas, peppers, spinach, squash, and zucchini.</p>=0A<p>Fruits: App=\r\nles, apricots, avocados, berries of all kinds, cantaloupes, cherries, cucum=\r\nber, figs, grapes, honeydew melon, kiwis, lemons, limes, nectarines, orange=\r\ns, peaches, pears, plums, tangerines, and tomatoes.</p>=0A<p>Legumes (less =\r\nthan 10% of your total calories): Black beans, chickpeas, fava beans, kidne=\r\ny beans, lentils, lima beans, navy beans, peas, and pinto beans.</p>=0A<p>G=\r\nrains and unprocessed grain products (less than 10% of your total calories)=\r\n: Brown rice, whole rice, wild rice, barley, whole oats, whole wheat, whole=\r\n grain, and buckwheat pastas.</p>=0A<p>Fats: Coconut, olive, canola, flaxse=\r\ned, and fish oils, seeds, nuts, and dairy products from pasture-fed animal =\r\nsources.</p>=0A<p>&nbsp;</p>=0A<h2>4. Any advice for us vegetarians?</h2>=\r\n=0A<p>You may have noticed that we encourage the consumption of animal prod=\r\nucts as part of a healthy diet. If, for any reason, you do not eat animal p=\r\nroteins, following a healthy vegetarian diet without overdosing on carbs is=\r\n absolutely possible. Even without meat, you can consume the proteins and f=\r\nats your diet needs, steer clear of the giant bowls of pasta, and not starv=\r\ne.</p>=0A<p>While carnivores have to be careful not to overdo the ribs, the=\r\n pitfalls for vegetarians can be even more detrimental. If you don=E2=80=99=\r\nt eat meat and you find that you=E2=80=99re hungry more than is normal, you=\r\nr first instinct may be to reach for empty carbs for quick energy. However,=\r\n you=E2=80=99d be much better off increasing the good fats from vegetable s=\r\nources in your diet, and upping your vegetable and legume intake. Feed your=\r\n body!</p>=0A<p>&nbsp;</p>=0A<h2>5. So are carbs pure evil?</h2>=0A<p>No, c=\r\narbs aren=E2=80=99t evil, but they=E2=80=99re not your best friends, either=\r\n. Prior to the first agricultural revolution 10,000 years ago, when humans =\r\nmade the major transition from a society of hunter-gatherers to one of agra=\r\nrian farmers, people lived (and thrived) on meat, seeds, nuts, fruits and v=\r\negetables. Our primitive ancestors ate no bread, no pasta, no crackers. Chi=\r\ncken didn=E2=80=99t come with a side of rice and if there=E2=80=99d been a =\r\nfood pyramid, those golden shafts of wheat would not have featured prominen=\r\ntly. People lived for 1.7 million year with almost no carbs=E2=80=94their o=\r\nnly carbohydrates came from fruits and vegetables.</p>=0A<p>Today, we live =\r\nin a world totally dominated by convenience carbs. The rampant production o=\r\nf grains has played a pivotal role in the shaping of modern society=E2=80=\r\n=94the way populations have grown, countries have formed, and wars have bee=\r\nn fought. Sometimes finding a piece of meat not served on a bed of pasta, r=\r\nice, or accompanied by a two-pound loaf of bread seems impossible.</p>=0A<p=\r\n>Despite the abundance of the American supermarket, the average American ea=\r\nts far too many processed cereal grains (about 50%), and not nearly enough =\r\nfruits, vegetables, and wholesome forms of protein. Carbs aren=E2=80=99t al=\r\nl bad, but if you make them too big a part of your diet, you=E2=80=99re mis=\r\nsing out on far superior sources of nutrition. Indeed, much empirical evide=\r\nnce reveals that in countries where processed grains comprise the national =\r\ndiet, vitamin, mineral and nutritional deficiencies are commonplace.</p>=0A=\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>=0A<h2>6. What should I eat in preparation for a <em>Power of =\r\n10</em> workout?</h2>=0A<p>We are so glad that you asked that question, bec=\r\nause one of the best times when some carbs would be good for you is before =\r\na workout with us. Carbs can provide the quick energy you need when you=E2=\r\n=80=99re on the go or about to work out. If you=E2=80=99re on your way to t=\r\nhe gym and your stomach is growling, eat an apple or orange. You=E2=80=99ll=\r\n get a boost from the fruit=E2=80=99s natural sugar and your body will than=\r\nk you. But, PLEASE, don=E2=80=99t eat a bagel and send your blood sugar thr=\r\nough the roof. Do yourself a favor and stick with natural and real whole-en=\r\nergy sources.</p>=0A<p>&nbsp;</p>=0A<h2>7. Hydration</h2>=0A<p>Whether you=\r\n=E2=80=99re doing a <em>Power of 10</em> workout or not, pure, clean water =\r\nis vital to your health! Hydrate with at least 8 glasses of water per day, =\r\nand more if you can.</p>=0A<p>Water promotes healthy cell function, muscle =\r\ngrowth, the elimination of body toxins, and especially the efficient metabo=\r\nlizing of fat. In extreme survival situations, you can survive for almost a=\r\n month without food, but after even a day or two without water, you=E2=80=\r\n=99re in serious trouble. So, again, hydrate! Drinking plenty of water will=\r\n make you look better, feel better, and lose weight.</p>=0A<p>&nbsp;</p>=0A=\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>=0A\t\t\t\t   =0D=0A                </div>=0D=0A                =\r\n=0D=0A                =0D=0A                <span class=3D\"clear\">&nbsp;</s=\r\npan> =0D=0A                <!-- main contents ends -->=0D=0A            </s=\r\nection>\t=0D=0A id=\r\n=3D\"maincontents\">=0D=0A        =0D=0A            <section id=3D\"contents\" =\r\nclass=3D\"grid_8\" style=3D\"padding-top:20px;\">=0D=0A\t\t\t\t<div id=3D\"blog\">=0D=\r\n=0A\t\t\t\t                    <div id=3D\"breadcrumbs\">=0D=0A                  =\r\n      <!-- Breadcrumb NavXT 4.1.0 -->=0A<span id=3D\"bstart\" style=3D\"color:=\r\n#666666;font-weight:bold;\">You are here:</span> <a style=3D\"color:#666666;\"=\r\n title=3D\"Go to Home.\" href=3D\"http://informfitness.com\">Home</a> &gt; <a s=\r\ntyle=3D\"color:#666666;\" title=3D\"Go to Blog.\" href=3D\"http://informfitness.=\r\ncom/blog/\">Blog</a> &gt; <a style=3D\"color:#666666;\" title=3D\"Go to the Hea=\r\nlth category archives.\" href=3D\"http://informfitness.com/blog/category/heal=\r\nth/\">Health</a> &gt; Cardiac Damage From Endurance Exercise                =\r\n    </div>                 =0D=0A                \t<section class=3D\"blogcon=\r\ntent\">=0D=0A                        <h2 class=3D\"blogh\"><a href=3D\"http://i=\r\nnformfitness.com/blog/strength-test-post/\">Cardiac Damage From Endurance Ex=\r\nercise</a></h2>=0D=0A                    \t<div class=3D\"meta\">=0D=0A       =\r\n                 \t<span class=3D\"time\"></span>9 December, 2011             =\r\n               <span class=3D\"cat\"></span><a href=3D\"http://informfitness.c=\r\nom/blog/category/health/\" title=3D\"View all posts in Health\" rel=3D\"categor=\r\ny tag\">Health</a>, <a href=3D\"http://informfitness.com/blog/category/streng=\r\nth/\" title=3D\"View all posts in Strength\" rel=3D\"category tag\">Strength</a>=\r\n                        </div> =0D=0A                        <div class=3D\"=\r\nborder\">&nbsp;</div>=0D=0A                        <div class=3D\"clear:both;=\r\n\">&nbsp;</div>                       =0D=0A                        <p><a hr=\r\nef=3D\"http://informfitness.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/49_running_legs.j=\r\npg\"><img class=3D\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-273\" title=3D\"49_running_l=\r\negs\" src=3D\"http://informfitness.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/49_running_=\r\nlegs-300x210.jpg\" alt=3D\"\" width=3D\"300\" height=3D\"210\" /></a>From MedPage =\r\nToday, Dec 6, 2011:</p>=0A<p>Intense endurance exercise &#8212; such as run=\r\nning a marathon &#8212; may induce cardiac damage confined to the right ven=\r\ntricle, a small study showed.</p>=0A<p>Highly trained endurance athletes ha=\r\nd reductions in right ventricular function immediately after a race, althou=\r\ngh it mostly returned to normal about a week later, according to Andr=C3=A9=\r\n La Gerche, MBBS, PhD, of the University of Melbourne in Australia, and col=\r\nleagues.</p>=0A<p>However, a handful of the athletes had signs of subclinic=\r\nal myocardial scarring on cardiac MRI, &#8220;suggesting that repetitive ul=\r\ntra-endurance exercise may lead to more extensive right ventricular change =\r\nand possible myocardial fibrosis,&#8221; the researchers reported online in=\r\n the European Heart Journal.</p>=0A<p><strong>Action Points:</strong><br />=\r\n=0A* This study of 40 endurance athletes found evidence of right ventricula=\r\nr effects after an endurance event that largely resolved by six to 11 days =\r\nlater.</p>=0A<p>* Also, no concomitant left ventricular effects were observ=\r\ned.</p>=0A<p>There were no changes in left ventricular function, which &#82=\r\n20;provides further circumstantial evidence for the emerging concept that t=\r\nhe right ventricle may be more susceptible to exercise-induced injury [than=\r\n the left],&#8221; they wrote.</p>=0A<p>The study included 40 athletes (mea=\r\nn age 37) who were participating in a marathon, an endurance triathlon, an =\r\nalpine cycling race, or an ultra triathlon. All trained for more than 10 ho=\r\nurs a week and had finished in the top quarter of a recent endurance race. =\r\nNone had cardiac symptoms or risk factors.</p>=0A<p>The researchers evaluat=\r\ned the athletes two to three weeks before the race, immediately after the r=\r\nace, and six to 11 days after the race.</p>=0A<p>Compared with baseline, ri=\r\nght ventricular volumes increased, and all measures of right ventricular fu=\r\nnction worsened immediately post race. Left ventricular function was unaffe=\r\ncted.</p>=0A<p>Levels of two biomarkers of myocardial injury &#8212; cardia=\r\nc troponin I and B-type natriuretic peptide &#8212; significantly increased=\r\n following the race (P=E2=89=A40.003 for both). The changes were associated=\r\n with reductions in right ventricular ejection fraction (P=E2=89=A40.002 fo=\r\nr both), but were unrelated to left ventricular ejection fraction.</p>=0A<p=\r\n>Lower right ventricular ejection fraction was significantly associated wit=\r\nh longer race duration and increasing peak oxygen uptake (P=E2=89=A40.011 f=\r\nor both).</p>=0A<p>By six to 11 days after the race, most measures of right=\r\n ventricular function had returned to normal, with the exception of right v=\r\nentricular strain rates, which remained lower.</p>=0A<p>In the 39 athletes =\r\nwho underwent cardiac MRI, five had delayed gadolinium enhancement confined=\r\n to the interventricular septum, indicative of subclinical myocardial fibro=\r\nsis. These athletes had been competing in endurance sports longer and had l=\r\nower right ventricular ejection fractions compared with those with normal M=\r\nRI findings.</p>=0A<p>Because the study was not powered to assess clinical =\r\noutcomes, the significance of the MRI findings requires further study, acco=\r\nrding to the authors.</p>=0A<p>The study &#8220;begs the hypothetical quest=\r\nion whether repetitive longstanding bouts of arduous exercise result in the=\r\n development of an acquired form of arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardio=\r\nmyopathy,&#8221; Sanjay Sharma, MD, and Abbas Zaidi, MBBS, of St. George&#8=\r\n217;s University of London, wrote in an accompanying editorial.</p>=0A<p>&#=\r\n8220;The results provide food for thought and the data should be embraced t=\r\no galvanize more detailed and longitudinal assessment of large groups of en=\r\ndurance athletes,&#8221; they wrote. &#8220;The potential for such projects=\r\n is enormous considering the colossal increase in participation rates in en=\r\ndurance events such as the marathon.&#8221;</p>=0A                        <=\r\ndiv style=3D\"clear:both;margin-bottom:20px;\">&nbsp;</div>  =0D=0A          =\r\n          </section>=0D=0A=0D=0A\t\t\t\t\t=0A<!-- You can start editing here. -->=\r\n=0A=0A=0A\t\t\t<!-- If comments are open, but there are no comments. -->=0A=0A=\r\n\t =0A=0A=0A<div
